  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Mutual Funds</h2></div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the difference between SIP and lump sum investment?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>SIP (Systematic Investment Plan) involves investing a fixed amount regularly (monthly/weekly), while lump sum is a one-time investment. SIP benefits from rupee cost averaging — you buy more units when NAV is low and fewer when high, reducing average cost over time. Lump sum can deliver higher returns if invested when markets are low. For most investors, SIP is recommended as it removes the need to time the market.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Are mutual funds safe? Can I lose money?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Mutual funds are market-linked instruments, so returns are not guaranteed and capital loss is possible in the short term. However, historically, diversified equity mutual funds have delivered positive returns over 5+ year periods. The key is choosing the right fund category for your risk appetite and staying invested for the recommended time horizon. Debt funds carry lower risk but are not completely risk-free.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>How are mutual fund returns taxed?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Equity funds: Short-term capital gains (held less than 1 year) are taxed at 20%. Long-term gains above ₹1.25 lakh per year are taxed at 12.5%. Debt funds: Gains are added to income and taxed at slab rate regardless of holding period (post-2023 rules). ELSS funds enjoy Section 80C deduction up to ₹1.5 lakh on the investment amount.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the minimum amount to invest in mutual funds?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>You can start a SIP with as little as ₹500 per month in most mutual funds (some allow ₹100). For lump sum investments, the minimum is typically ₹1,000–₹5,000 depending on the fund. There is no maximum limit. This low entry barrier makes mutual funds accessible to virtually everyone.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>How do I choose the right mutual fund?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Consider these factors: (1) Your financial goal and time horizon, (2) Risk tolerance — conservative investors should prefer large cap or debt funds, (3) Fund's track record over 3–5–10 years, (4) Expense ratio — lower is better, (5) Fund manager's experience and consistency, (6) AUM size — very large or very small AUM can be disadvantageous. Our advisors can help you select the optimal fund based on your specific situation.</p></div></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

